  "slug": "vegetable-biryani",
  "title": "Vegetable biryani",
  "subtitle": "Layered rice and spiced vegetables, sealed and steamed.",
  "excerpt": "Basmati par-cooked with whole spice, layered with a thick spiced vegetable masala, sealed in a lidded pot and steamed for 25 minutes. The classic Hyderabadi dum technique, the vegetarian household version.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The dum technique of sealed steam-cooking is documented in Indian regional food writing from the Mughal courts through to the modern home kitchen. This is the household vegetarian version, not the formal banquet style.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Biryani works on two pots and one assembly. In the first, basmati rice is half-cooked with whole spices in salted water and drained. In the second, the vegetable masala is built up: onions fried hard, ginger and garlic in, yoghurt-marinated vegetables added, simmered down until thick and dark. Then the two go together in layers (rice, masala, rice, masala, rice on top), and the pot is sealed and steamed for 25 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The rice has to be 70 to 80 percent cooked when it goes into the layers, not fully done. It finishes cooking in the steam. The masala should be thick enough to sit in heaps, not pour: too wet and the rice goes mushy at the bottom.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
