      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A heavy lidded casserole or Dutch oven of at least 4 litres for the dum. The lid needs to fit tightly; a sheet of foil between pan and lid seals it properly.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Par-cook the rice",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring 3 litres of water to the boil in a large saucepan. Add {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, the {{cinnamon-stick}} of cinnamon, {{cardamom-green}} of cardamom, {{cloves}} of cloves, and {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves. Drop in the soaked {{basmati-rice}} of rice. Cook for 5 to 6 minutes only: the grains should still have a hard core when bitten. Drain in a fine sieve over the sink.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the masala",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{vegetable-oil}} of oil in the casserole over medium-high. Add {{onion}} of sliced onions. Cook for 12 to 14 minutes, stirring often, until deep brown and crisp at the edges. Lift two-thirds out onto kitchen paper with a slotted spoon, leaving the rest in the pan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "To the onions left in the pan, add {{garlic}} of crushed garlic, {{ginger-root}} of crushed ginger, and the slit green chilli. Stir for 1 minute. Add {{coriander-ground}} of coriander, {{cumin-ground}} of cumin, {{turmeric}} of turmeric, and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Stir for 30 seconds.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whisk {{greek-yoghurt}} of yoghurt smooth in a separate bowl. Pour it into the pan and stir for 2 minutes; this stops it curdling. Add {{potato}} of potato, {{carrot}} of carrot, {{cauliflower}} of cauliflower, {{green-beans}} of green beans, and {{peas-frozen}} of peas. Pour in 200 ml of water. Cover and simmer for 12 to 15 minutes until the potato is tender. Uncover and bubble for 3 minutes to thicken the gravy until it's spoonable, not pourable. Stir in {{garam-masala}} of garam masala.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Layer and seal",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Spread half the masala in a single layer in the casserole. Top with half the par-cooked rice in an even layer. Scatter half the reserved crisp onions, half the {{mint}} of chopped mint, half the {{coriander}} of chopped coriander. Repeat with the rest. Drizzle the saffron milk and the {{ghee}} of melted ghee over the top.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cover the pan with a sheet of foil, pressed down around the edges. Set the lid on top. Cook on the lowest possible heat for 25 minutes; on a gas hob, use a heat-diffuser if you have one. The rice steams in its own moisture.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest and serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lift the pan off the heat and let it rest, sealed, for 15 minutes. Open at the table. Stir gently to mix the layers as you serve. Eat with a raita of yoghurt, cucumber, and mint.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Cook the masala until it sits in heaps with no free liquid. Par-cook the rice only 5 to 6 minutes, with a hard core still in the grain when bitten.",
              "cause": "Masala too wet, or rice cooked too long before layering.",
              "symptom": "Rice mushy at the bottom of the pan"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use the lowest possible setting on the hob. A heat-diffuser plate under a gas burner is a good investment for this dish.",
              "cause": "Heat too high during the dum.",
              "symptom": "Bottom layer burnt"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Press a sheet of foil over the rim before the lid goes on. The steam needs to stay trapped.",
              "cause": "Lid not properly sealed.",
              "symptom": "Top rice dry while bottom is wet"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Whisk the yoghurt smooth first. Stir constantly for 2 minutes as it goes in, on medium not high heat.",
              "cause": "Yoghurt added cold to a hot pan without stirring.",
              "symptom": "Yoghurt curdled in the masala"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Biryani is the dish of weddings, celebrations, and Sunday lunches across the subcontinent. The Hyderabadi style (kacchi biryani, where raw marinated meat goes into the layers) is the most famous; the vegetable version here uses pakka technique, where the masala is fully cooked before layering. Serve with raita, a wedge of lemon, and a green chilli pickle to one side.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
